title: SFH visits Wan Chai (with photos)
content_text:
p>
    The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr York Chow, today (July 6) visited Wan 
    Chai to familiarise himself with the latest developments in the district. Accompanied by Wan Chai District Officer, Miss Angela Luk, Dr Chow first 
    visited True Light Middle School of Hong Kong to see life in the school and 
    its learning environment, and to exchange views with teachers and students 
    on healthcare and other current issues. Dr Chow also attended a 
    demonstration by students of their Passing-of-the-Light ceremony and

demonstration by students of their Passing-of-the-Light ceremony and 
    marching performance. During this traditional school ceremony, form five 
    graduates will pass the "Light of Truth" on to form four students, 
    symbolising the succession of the school spirit from generation to 
    generation. Dr Chow then visited the Community Health Call Centre Telephone Nursing 
    Consultation Service (TNCS) in Tang Shiu Kin Hospital. Launched by the Hong 
    Kong East Cluster in 2003, the telephone consultation and support service

Kong East Cluster in 2003, the telephone consultation and support service 
    aims to provide support for high-risk discharged elderly patients. Under the 
    pilot scheme, nurses will co-ordinate with hospitals and community 
    healthcare and service units, and closely monitor the health condition of 
    the elders by telephone. The nurses will also assess the health condition of 
    the elders, conduct triage assessment, and provide referral and health 
    advice according to clinical protocols. Dr Chow said he was pleased to learn that since it started service, the TNCS

has served more than 15,000 patients, and among these patients, the utility 
    rate of emergency medical care service and the death rate have been reduced 
    significantly. Noting that the staff of the centre had been awarded for 
    being one of this year's outstanding staff and teams of the Hospital 
    Authority, Dr Chow commended the team for their professionalism and hard 
    work in providing quality services to patients. Dr Chow concluded his visit at a tea gathering with district councillors, 
    with whom he exchanged views and experiences on how to improve services in

with whom he exchanged views and experiences on how to improve services in health, food safety and environmental hygiene. Ends/Tuesday, July 6, 2010
